Abstract
This paper examines the growing adoption of decentralized storage systems 
in academic research institutions. As research data grows exponentially, 
traditional centralized storage solutions face challenges in scalability, 
accessibility, and long-term preservation. Decentralized storage networks 
offer promising alternatives through content-addressed storage, redundancy, 
and trustless data verification.

Introduction
Academic research generates vast amounts of data annually. From genomic 
sequences to climate models, the volume and complexity of research data 
has outpaced the capacity of traditional storage infrastructure. 
Institutions increasingly face challenges related to data loss, 
reproducibility, and cross-institutional collaboration.

Decentralized storage systems such as IPFS, Filecoin, and 0G Storage 
address these challenges by distributing data across multiple nodes, 
ensuring redundancy and censorship resistance. Unlike centralized systems, 
decentralized networks do not rely on a single point of failure.

Methodology
This study analyzed 50 research institutions across 12 countries over a 
period of 3 years. Data was collected through surveys, interviews, and 
direct system audits. Storage costs, retrieval speeds, and data integrity 
metrics were compared between centralized and decentralized solutions.

Results
Institutions using decentralized storage reported a 40% reduction in data 
loss incidents compared to those using traditional cloud storage. 
Retrieval times averaged 2.3 seconds for decentralized systems versus 
1.1 seconds for centralized systems, indicating a trade-off between 
speed and reliability. Storage costs were 35% lower on average for 
decentralized solutions over a 3-year period.

Conclusion
Decentralized storage presents a viable and cost-effective alternative 
for academic research data management. While retrieval speeds remain 
slightly slower than centralized systems, the benefits of redundancy, 
cost savings, and data integrity make decentralized solutions 
increasingly attractive for long-term research data preservation.

